Human TP53 Gene (Tumor Protein p53)

The TP53 gene is one of the most studied tumor suppressor genes in humans and plays a critical role in regulating cell cycle arrest, apoptosis, and DNA repair mechanisms. Mutations in this gene are strongly associated with many cancers, making it highly important in medical genetics and molecular oncology.

This sequence is useful for mutation analysis, SNP identification, promoter studies, and comparative genomics. It is commonly used in cancer bioinformatics pipelines and molecular diagnostics research. You can also perform ORF prediction and protein translation analysis using this sequence.
